properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Snow, ice pellets and possible freezing rain for Sunday night and into Monday morning. Snow will begin over western New Brunswick this evening, then continue into Monday afternoon over the northeast. Generally snowfall amounts of 15 to 20 cm can be expected in heaviest areas where warnings have been issued. Central regions of the province will see a mix of rain, snow, ice pellets, and freezing rain tonight and Monday. Some areas could see a period of freezing rain tonight, including areas from Woodstock to Stanley and south towards Fredericton. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NBstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NBStorm.

properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Significant snowfall for the middle of the week. Significant snowfall amounts and local blowing snow are expected over several regions of Quebec. An intense low pressure system from Colorado will reach Quebec on Wednesday. Snow will begin gradually Wednesday morning over Western Quebec, then will spread to central regions in the evening. The exact track of this weather system could still change, which could impact the type and amount of precipitation. The snowfall may make travelling difficult. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to QCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #QCStorm.

properties.Title: Update: High Water Advisory Alert Is Being Issued For The Roseau River From Gardenton To Stuartburn
properties.Summary:
Description: Update: This is a Manitoba Emergency Alert. Manitoba Infrastructure's Hydrologic Forecast Centre has issued a High Water Advisory for the Roseau River from Gardenton to Stuartburn due to expected high flows. If you are in the affected area, be watchful of local waterways as flooding is likely to occur. Do not attempt to cross fast flowing waters or waters of unknown depth. Avoid flooded areas. Follow all directions by the local authorities. Listen for updates and take all necessary precautions to stay safe. Up-to-date information is available at www.gov.mb.ca/flooding and www.manitoba511.ca or stay tuned to local media.
Expires: 2019-11-25T11:30:00-06:00

Area: Roseau River from Gardenton to Stuartburn

properties.Title: Snowfall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Snow continuing this morning. Snow will taper to flurries by this afternoon. Additional accumulations of generally 2 to 4 cm are expected, with potential for up to 10 cm in areas of heaviest snowfall. ### Rapidly accumulating snow could make travel difficult over some locations. There may be a significant impact on rush hour traffic in urban areas. Snowfall warnings are issued when significant snowfall is expected. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NBstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NBStorm.

properties.Title: Winter Storm Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Hazardous winter conditions are expected. Snow, freezing rain and ice pellets for tonight and Monday. Freezing rain mixed with ice pellets will spread northward across the region this evening and then change back to snow overnight. Snow will then continue into Monday afternoon, with total accumulations of 15 to 20 cm expected. ### Surfaces such as highways, roads, walkways and parking lots will become icy, slippery and hazardous. Winter storm warnings are issued when multiple types of severe winter weather are expected to occur together. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NBstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NBStorm.

properties.Title: Les Suêtes Wind Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Very strong wind gusts that may cause damage are expected or occurring. Les Suêtes winds gusting to 130 km/h will diminish later this morning. ### High winds may cause downed trees or toss loose objects. Les Suêtes wind warnings are issued when there is a significant risk of damaging winds. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NSstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NSStorm.
